# Cursor Rules for Unity C# Project

## Project Context
This is a Unity C# project (Unity 2022.3.0f1 or later). The project uses standard Unity conventions and structure.

## Coding Standards
- Use C# coding conventions (PascalCase for public members, camelCase for private members)
- Follow Unity's MonoBehaviour patterns
- Use meaningful variable and method names
- Add XML documentation comments for public APIs
- Keep scripts modular and focused on single responsibilities

## Unity-Specific Guidelines
- When creating new scripts, inherit from MonoBehaviour for component-based scripts
- Use [SerializeField] for private fields that should be visible in the Inspector
- Use [Header], [Tooltip], and [Range] attributes to improve Inspector usability
- Prefer using Unity's built-in components and systems when possible
- Use Time.deltaTime for frame-rate independent movement
- Cache component references in Awake/Start rather than accessing them every frame

## File Organization
- Place scripts in `Assets/Scripts/` directory
- Organize scripts by feature/component
- Use namespaces to organize related code

## Best Practices
- Avoid Update() loops when possible; use events or coroutines instead
- Use object pooling for frequently instantiated objects
- Keep scripts focused on a single responsibility
- Use ScriptableObjects for data-driven design
- Follow Unity's performance best practices

